  "prompt": "Why does iOS still regularly demand a passcode, when a fingerprint is surely more secure?",
  "response": "There are a few important reasons why iOS still requires periodic passcode entry, even with Touch ID or Face ID:\n\n1. Security protocol\n- Biometric authentication can be temporarily disabled or bypassed\n- Passcode provides a fallback authentication method\n- After a certain number of failed biometric attempts, the device requires a passcode\n\n2. Legal considerations\n- In some jurisdictions, biometric unlock can be legally compelled, but passcodes cannot\n- Passcode provides stronger legal protection of device contents\n\n3. Technical limitations\n- Biometric sensors can occasionally fail or become less accurate\n- Passcode ensures users can always access their device\n- Some situations like wearing gloves or having obscured facial features can prevent biometric unlock\n\n4. Apple's security design\n- Periodic passcode entry helps prevent unauthorized biometric spoofing\n- Ensures the user actively confirms their identity\n- Part of multi-factor authentication strategy\n\n5. Specific trigger points for passcode requirement\n- After device restart\n- After 48 hours of inactivity\n- When not unlocked for a certain period\n- After multiple failed biometric attempts\n\nThese policies help maintain a balance between convenience and robust device security.",
